<subSubSection id="67D870BAC12150F6A58869A09D798468" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph id="0513711EAFCB6A6078ACF6B7E4368867" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0B0D338C9E6EE5E722720847F35F36BA" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421">
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName id="64455DA122B38D8F0745F9D6E1C40548" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Thelypteris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Thelypteris (Steiropteris) decussata" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="decussata" subGenus="Steiropteris">Thelypteris (Steiropteris) decussata</taxonomicName>
(L.) Proctor, but differs from it by the costae abaxially with dense, soft, septate hairs 1-2 mm long, costules and veins adaxially with dense, strigose hairs up to 2 mm (
<bibRefCitation id="AD3F813754200C9B1313DF21B4D4087C" author="Tryon, R. M." journalOrPublisher="Fieldiana, Botany New Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" pagination="1 - 80" title="Pteridophyta of Peru. Part III. 16. Thelypteridaceae" volume="29" year="1992">Tryon et al. 1992</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
